111
00:04:52,019 --> 00:04:53,060
they kinda look the same,

112
00:04:53,060 --> 00:04:55,902
so that means we can animate them the same, right?

113
00:04:55,902 --> 00:04:59,465
But actually, a key thing changed between our two games,

114
00:04:59,465 --> 00:05:01,587
how far away the camera was.

115
00:05:01,587 --> 00:05:03,028
In Skullgirls, our fighting game,

116
00:05:03,028 --> 00:05:04,489
the characters are large on screen

117
00:05:04,489 --> 00:05:07,192
because they essentially are the entire game.

118
00:05:07,192 --> 00:05:09,153
Subtle touches came across in the animations

119
00:05:09,153 --> 00:05:10,795
because they were just so big.

120
00:05:13,086 --> 00:05:15,887
And then we started to animate our second game, Indivisible,

121
00:05:15,887 --> 00:05:16,907
which is a platforming RPG.

122
00:05:16,907 --> 00:05:20,509
And we actually quickly realized that we couldn't approach it

123
00:05:20,509 --> 00:05:22,209
in exactly the same way.

124
00:05:22,209 --> 00:05:24,690
We zoomed out the camera, and a lot of the detail

125
00:05:24,690 --> 00:05:26,551
we had put into Skullgirl's characters

126
00:05:26,551 --> 00:05:30,312
just became noise when viewed from the zoom in Indivisible.

127
00:05:30,312 --> 00:05:31,973
