128
00:05:31,973 --> 00:05:34,373
Our animations, our characters, we just kind of

129
00:05:34,373 --> 00:05:36,234
had to re-look at what we were doing.

130
00:05:36,234 --> 00:05:39,255
Subtle animations had to be exaggerated a lot more,

131
00:05:39,255 --> 00:05:41,116
just so you could actually see them on the screen.

132
00:05:43,542 --> 00:05:45,323
And this doesn't just apply to us.

133
00:05:45,323 --> 00:05:47,004
What kind of game are you making?

134
00:05:47,004 --> 00:05:49,485
Are you viewing your character from the side,

135
00:05:49,485 --> 00:05:51,045
the top down, is it first person?

136
00:05:51,045 --> 00:05:53,427
If you're working on something like League of Legends

137
00:05:53,427 --> 00:05:55,707
or Diablo where your animations are viewed from above,

138
00:05:55,707 --> 00:05:56,928
you might not see expressions

139
00:05:56,928 --> 00:05:58,909
that you want to animate on the character.

140
00:05:58,909 --> 00:06:01,030
You even need to approach your key poses differently

141
00:06:01,030 --> 00:06:03,091
because your silhouette reads differently from the top.

142
00:06:03,771 --> 00:06:07,972
If you're working on a first-person game and you can run right up to an NPC or a monster,

143
00:06:07,972 --> 00:06:12,594
you might want to put facial animations or subtle idols in there to create better immersion in that

144
00:06:12,594 --> 00:06:17,375
