00:11:15,982 --> 00:11:19,364
while the character is dashing down a hallway towards impending doom,

253
00:11:19,364 --> 00:11:21,986
but if it loses the audience, the shot will be a failure.

254
00:11:21,986 --> 00:11:24,908
So keep it simple and keep it clear. It will still look cool.

255
00:11:26,009 --> 00:11:29,212
As I read this, it really hit home to me about first person

256
00:11:29,212 --> 00:11:32,454
because as Matt pointed out, we have staging,

257
00:11:32,454 --> 00:11:34,496
which is something that's kind of rare in game animation.

258
00:11:34,496 --> 00:11:36,417
We know where the camera is and we can act,

259
00:11:36,417 --> 00:11:38,119
do our performance to that.

260
00:11:38,119 --> 00:11:41,982
But we need to make sure that we're not making the audience sick

261
00:11:41,982 --> 00:11:44,083
or that we're not doing something that distracts

262
00:11:44,083 --> 00:11:45,304
from what's actually happening.

263
00:11:45,304 --> 00:11:49,007
So keep it simple, keep it clear.

264
00:11:49,007 --> 00:11:50,889
You don't want that.

265
00:11:50,889 --> 00:11:52,330
Do not over design the action.

266
00:11:53,817 --> 00:11:56,378
Don't rush the key information,

267
00:11:56,378 --> 00:11:59,100
and do not put style ahead of readability.

268
00:11:59,100 --> 00:12:02,042
It's something that's really difficult to do.

269
00:12:02,042 --> 00:12:03,604
When you first jump in to first person,

270
00:12:03,604 --> 00:12:05,605
all you wanna do is do the coolest thing possible,

271
00:12:05,605 --> 00:12:06,286
and you've got this gun,

272
00:12:06,286 --> 00:12:08,247
and you're gonna spin it and flip it.

273
00:12:08,247 --> 00:12:09,588
But if you're doing these complex actions

274
00:12:09,588 --> 00:12:11,309
and people can't follow what's happening,

275
00:12:11,309 --> 00:12:15,612
you're gonna lose out on the audience very quickly.

276
00:12:15,612 --> 00:12:16,673
But what you do wanna do

277
00:12:16,673 --> 00:12:21,757
is simplify the action into what I call key beats.

278
00:12:23,547 --> 00:12:25,549
Use holds for understanding.

279
00:12:25,549 --> 00:12:27,732
It typically takes four to six frames

280
00:12:27,732 --> 00:12:30,555
for the viewer to absorb information.

281
00:12:30,555 --> 00:12:31,956
And then apply style to the beats.

282
00:12:31,956 --> 00:12:34,499
And what I mean by style is your character

283
00:12:34,499 --> 00:12:35,940
or the weapon's personality.

284
00:12:36,997 --> 00:12:38,198
And then clarity is king.

285
00:12:38,198 --> 00:12:39,720
It's the most important thing.

286
00:12:39,720 --> 00:12:43,083
So this is an animation that I did

287
00:12:43,083 --> 00:12:46,367
for this like kind of futuristic gunslinger guy.

288
00:12:46,367 --> 00:12:47,668
And I think it kind of represents

289
00:12:47,668 --> 00:12:49,150
everything that I was talking about.

290
00:12:49,150 --> 00:12:50,632
You can see the chamber opening

291
00:12:50,632 --> 00:12:53,155
when the gun's energy core depletes.

292
00:12:53,155 --> 00:12:56,138
The gun winds up to repower the core

293
00:12:56,138 --> 00:12:57,820
and then the chamber closes with a snap.

294
00:12:58,718 --> 00:13:01,179
So what I did is I identified these key beats,

295
00:13:01,179 --> 00:13:04,341
and then with it being this idea of a futuristic gunslinger

296
00:13:04,341 --> 00:13:06,683
and like this techno revolver,

297
00:13:06,683 --> 00:13:08,624
I applied the style to those beats.

298
00:13:08,624 --> 00:13:10,465
So instead of the chord just opening up

299
00:13:10,465 --> 00:13:12,366
and then going back in, he spins it around,

300
00:13:12,366 --> 00:13:16,929
flips it, kind of snaps it back in.

301
00:13:16,929 --> 00:13:19,731
And lastly, layers are for detail.

302
00:13:21,823 --> 00:13:24,786
So this is a simple tip that our lead animator at BossKey

303
00:13:24,786 --> 00:13:27,269
shared with me when I first came on board.

304
00:13:27,269 --> 00:13:29,091
And I was just getting started in first person.

305
00:13:29,091 --> 00:13:31,674
And honestly, I think it applies to first person,

306
00:13:31,674 --> 00:13:34,777
third person, or just animation in general.

307
00:13:34,777 --> 00:13:37,320
It's a simple no-brainer, but sometimes you gloss over

308
00:13:37,320 --> 00:13:38,821
things like this.

309
00:13:38,821 --> 00:13:41,184
But use your layers for the details,

310
00:13:41,184 --> 00:13:43,587
and the details are what brings your animations to life.

311
00:13:47,004 --> 00:13:50,145
So this is an example of a gun that I designed,

312
00:13:50,145 --> 00:13:52,346
worked with a concept artist.

313
00:13:52,346 --> 00:13:54,147
Same character, he's got two guns,

314
00:13:54,147 --> 00:13:56,669
and he's gotta reload them independently

315
00:13:56,669 --> 00:13:59,490
because while this one's reloading, he can shoot,

316
00:13:59,490 --> 00:14:00,791
so he can't use both of his hands.

317
00:14:00,791 --> 00:14:02,792
So we had to design these guns to be reloaded

318
00:14:02,792 --> 00:14:05,073
without touching them with another hand.

319
00:14:05,073 --> 00:14:08,055
So in this animation, it's super simple.

320
00:14:08,055 --> 00:14:10,036
The gun just lifts up, it holds it there

321
00:14:10,036 --> 00:14:12,677
so that you can see that it's got a 3D printer

322
00:14:12,677 --> 00:14:15,098
that's printing a new ammo brick

323
00:14:15,098 --> 00:14:16,419
so that it can continue shooting.

324
00:14:17,039 --> 00:14:19,126
I really dig this, I think it's awesome,

325
00:14:19,126 --> 00:14:21,634
but as far as animation goes, it's really simple.

326
00:14:21,634 --> 00:14:23,881
So what I do is.

327
00:14:26,937 --> 00:14:28,418
I don't have as many layers as Matt.

328
00:14:28,418 --> 00:14:32,199
But this is a super simplified example.

329
00:14:32,199 --> 00:14:39,162
So what I use my base layer for is for my foundational movement on my overall timing,

330
00:14:39,162 --> 00:14:42,783
the big motions, and the base of the idea and getting that across.

331
00:14:42,783 --> 00:14:47,445
I go through that, I get that in, I put it in game because as you probably heard today,

332
00:14:47,445 --> 00:14:49,646
get it in game as soon as possible.

333
00:14:49,646 --> 00:14:52,367
Get it in game, start getting feedback.

334
00:14:52,367 --> 00:14:52,487
But

335
00:14:52,667 --> 00:14:55,088
going back to the animation, is super simple,

336
00:14:55,088 --> 00:14:57,189
but what brought that to life was the details,

337
00:14:57,189 --> 00:14:59,550
how the gun shakes when the ammo prints.

338
00:14:59,550 --> 00:15:01,931
And I knew there was gonna be a lot of iteration

