00:16:43,974 --> 00:16:46,676
All right, first tip.

376
00:16:46,676 --> 00:16:48,977
Don't start your hit reacts from the idle.

377
00:16:48,977 --> 00:16:53,280
I learned this when I was working on Reckoning.

378
00:16:53,280 --> 00:16:56,982
So we all know that video game is different from film.

379
00:16:56,982 --> 00:16:58,423
Video games is linear.

380
00:16:58,423 --> 00:16:59,543
I mean, sorry.

381
00:16:59,543 --> 00:17:00,324
Film is linear.

382
00:17:00,324 --> 00:17:02,865
Video game is more like a jigsaw puzzle.

383
00:17:02,865 --> 00:17:05,087
All the animations have to fit within each other, right?

384
00:17:05,087 --> 00:17:05,667
They have to connect.

385
00:17:05,667 --> 00:17:09,990
Now hit reacts are a little unique.

386
00:17:11,536 --> 00:17:14,417
that hit reacts have to, they need to feel satisfying

387
00:17:14,417 --> 00:17:17,657
and responsive, right?

388
00:17:17,657 --> 00:17:21,858
And most new animators will automatically animate

389
00:17:21,858 --> 00:17:26,399
the hit react starting from idle to hit frame

390
00:17:26,399 --> 00:17:28,700
to recovery, settle, back into idle again.

391
00:17:28,700 --> 00:17:32,680
That's how they think they should animate it.

392
00:17:32,680 --> 00:17:35,741
But when you do that, the result is kind of sluggish.

393
00:17:35,741 --> 00:17:36,901
It feels kind of slow, right?

394
00:17:36,901 --> 00:17:40,602
Okay.

395
00:17:40,602 --> 00:17:40,762
So.

396
00:17:42,319 --> 00:17:45,462
As you can see here, the animation right there,

397
00:17:45,462 --> 00:17:47,784
I mean, it's not the fault of the attack

398
00:17:47,784 --> 00:17:48,404
that makes it feel slow.

399
00:17:48,404 --> 00:17:51,647
Because you look, the attack feels like

400
00:17:51,647 --> 00:17:53,128
it's not really making contact.

401
00:17:53,128 --> 00:17:55,450
It feels a little sluggish, right?

402
00:17:55,450 --> 00:18:03,476
But we start the animation for the attack later

403
00:18:03,476 --> 00:18:05,638
at the recovery pose.

404
00:18:05,638 --> 00:18:08,801
Instantly, the player will see the attack.

405
00:18:08,801 --> 00:18:11,983
Visually, the attack is gonna be.

406
00:18:12,745 --> 00:18:15,127
Sorry, the react will be much bigger.

407
00:18:15,127 --> 00:18:19,911
The pose is bigger, you start from the recovery pose.

408
00:18:19,911 --> 00:18:22,593
So it's gonna be a much clearer read, quick and clear.

409
00:18:22,593 --> 00:18:28,598
So as you can see there, same attack,

410
00:18:28,598 --> 00:18:31,361
but a bigger, but the reaction started later,

411
00:18:31,361 --> 00:18:34,904
so it feels bigger, the impact is huge.

412
00:18:34,904 --> 00:18:37,966
The bigger you push the reaction pose,

413
00:18:37,966 --> 00:18:40,588
or the recovery pose, the bigger the action.

414
00:18:40,588 --> 00:18:41,229
I mean, the bigger,

415
00:18:41,690 --> 00:18:43,690
the attack will feel.

416
00:18:43,690 --> 00:18:45,271
And I always tell people,

417
00:18:45,271 --> 00:18:46,751
push this pose as big as you can,

418
00:18:46,751 --> 00:18:49,552
because if you want it to be impactful, make it big.

419
00:18:49,552 --> 00:18:53,233
That's tip number one, you're welcome.

420
00:18:53,233 --> 00:18:57,634
Tip number two.

421
00:18:57,634 --> 00:19:02,995
So this is a typical take that we see all animators do.

422
00:19:02,995 --> 00:19:05,116
We have anticipation, we have an overshoot,

423
00:19:05,116 --> 00:19:06,376
and then an action.

424
00:19:06,376 --> 00:19:09,377
Perfectly normal.

425
00:19:10,167 --> 00:19:14,389
The problem is, the majority of the time when you do this,

426
00:19:14,389 --> 00:19:17,170
you don't know why the character's doing it, right?

427
00:19:17,170 --> 00:19:20,030
This is what we normally see in games.

428
00:19:20,030 --> 00:19:23,572
Character stands around, player comes in,

429
00:19:23,572 --> 00:19:25,132
and he just freaks out.

430
00:19:25,132 --> 00:19:25,852
Like, just freaks out.

431
00:19:25,852 --> 00:19:27,773
Like, why are you here, ah!

432
00:19:27,773 --> 00:19:28,713
Right?

433
00:19:28,713 --> 00:19:32,515
We don't know why he's freaking out.

434
00:19:32,515 --> 00:19:32,755
So.

435
00:19:34,525 --> 00:19:37,447
What I tell young animators is to...

436
00:19:37,447 --> 00:19:39,208
Now this is mainly for NPCs,

437
00:19:39,208 --> 00:19:42,110
and it depends on gameplay, of course.

438
00:19:42,110 --> 00:19:45,132
But if you add a decision pose, a recognition pose,

439
00:19:45,132 --> 00:19:50,575
a pose where basically tells the viewer

440
00:19:50,575 --> 00:19:51,876
why he's reacting this way.

441
00:19:51,876 --> 00:19:55,659
A teacher of mine at CalArts told me

442
00:19:55,659 --> 00:20:01,082
that acting is reaction, is not action.

443
00:20:01,082 --> 00:20:03,023
So how your character reacts to something

444
00:20:03,023 --> 00:20:04,064
tells you who they are.

445
00:20:07,222 --> 00:20:11,304
Now this is very subtle, and depending on gameplay,

446
00:20:11,304 --> 00:20:14,125
you can spend more time in the decision post,

447
00:20:14,125 --> 00:20:15,386
give it more character.

448
00:20:15,386 --> 00:20:17,927
This is where you wanna add personality

449
00:20:17,927 --> 00:20:21,629
and subtext to your character, before the anticipation.

450
00:20:21,629 --> 00:20:22,990
People always ask me,

451
00:20:22,990 --> 00:20:25,791
how do I give it more personality and character?

452
00:20:25,791 --> 00:20:27,372
You do it before the anticipation,

453
00:20:27,372 --> 00:20:29,433
you do it before he actually does something.

454
00:20:29,433 --> 00:20:33,875
All right.

455
00:20:33,875 --> 00:20:34,996
Oh, sorry, you're welcome.

456
00:20:36,575 --> 00:20:41,338
Tip number three, use your hand as reference.

457
00:20:41,338 --> 00:20:43,440
Now I learned this the hard way.

458
00:20:43,440 --> 00:20:47,163
When you get a weird, crazy creature

459
00:20:47,163 --> 00:20:48,584
and you spend all this time trying to find

460
00:20:48,584 --> 00:20:50,385
the perfect reference, you're like,

461
00:20:50,385 --> 00:20:53,868
I need to find an animal with 20 tentacles,

462
00:20:53,868 --> 00:20:56,730
a large mouth, eight horns, and it's like,

463
00:20:56,730 --> 00:20:58,232
can't find that, that just doesn't exist.

464
00:20:58,232 --> 00:21:03,175
And if you guys seen that, run away.

465
00:21:03,175 --> 00:21:06,198
So, use your hand as reference.

466
00:21:08,545 --> 00:21:11,530
And how you want to use your hand as reference is basically

467
00:21:11,530 --> 00:21:14,615
you want to figure out the center of gravity.

468
00:21:15,613 --> 00:21:16,993
You want to figure out the weight.

469
00:21:16,993 --> 00:21:18,734
You want to figure out how it's going to be moving,

470
00:21:18,734 --> 00:21:21,494
how the weight is being pushed, pulled,

471
00:21:21,494 --> 00:21:24,035
how the weight is going to shift, how it's going to settle.

472
00:21:24,035 --> 00:21:27,016
Once you figure that out as animators,

473
00:21:27,016 --> 00:21:28,836
the body mechanics just follows, right?

474
00:21:28,836 --> 00:21:31,537
Because that's the core of animation.

475
00:21:31,537 --> 00:21:33,898
If we figure out the timing and spacing,

476
00:21:33,898 --> 00:21:35,638
we can figure out the rest.

477
00:21:35,638 --> 00:21:38,379
And I use my hands just to block things out a lot,

478
00:21:38,379 --> 00:21:39,959
just so I can get it out of there.

479
00:21:39,959 --> 00:21:41,600
So I figure that out quick,

480
00:21:41,600 --> 00:21:43,660
and then I can just block out the animation.

