00:34:41,026 --> 00:34:43,688
but it highlighted any tiny errors in the animation

771
00:34:43,688 --> 00:34:45,249
which might usually be covered.

772
00:34:45,249 --> 00:34:48,231
At that point in my career, I found it hard

773
00:34:48,231 --> 00:34:51,374
to see smaller issues during general playback.

774
00:34:51,374 --> 00:34:53,876
So scrubbing back and forth would highlight

775
00:34:53,876 --> 00:34:55,617
some of these errors but wouldn't give

776
00:34:55,617 --> 00:34:57,359
a true representation of what it would look like

777
00:34:57,359 --> 00:34:57,859
in the trailers.

778
00:34:59,153 --> 00:35:01,314
So I started playing animation back at a quarter speed

779
00:35:01,314 --> 00:35:03,155
to emphasize the issues,

780
00:35:03,155 --> 00:35:05,636
and it actually makes it easier to fix,

781
00:35:05,636 --> 00:35:07,137
allowing me to spin around and see everything

782
00:35:07,137 --> 00:35:08,518
much, much clearer.

783
00:35:08,518 --> 00:35:11,780
So for extra clarity, I turn on frames and ticks.

784
00:35:11,780 --> 00:35:13,460
Yeah, I use 3ds Max,

785
00:35:13,460 --> 00:35:16,322
which let you scrub areas in super slow motion.

786
00:35:16,322 --> 00:35:18,583
I'd use this to highlight a point to my team

787
00:35:18,583 --> 00:35:20,004
that was hard to see in real time.

788
00:35:20,004 --> 00:35:21,465
Maybe the arc of a junk locks off,

789
00:35:21,465 --> 00:35:24,026
the weight shift maybe is too aggressive.

790
00:35:24,026 --> 00:35:25,487
Play your animation in super slow motion,

791
00:35:25,487 --> 00:35:27,008
and you'll be surprised at what you actually see.

792
00:35:28,580 --> 00:35:31,641
but be careful of extensive timing changes.

793
