794
00:35:34,483 --> 00:35:36,504
So my third and final tip is how does it feel?

795
00:35:36,504 --> 00:35:39,386
Gameplay animation is not just about looking good.

796
00:35:39,386 --> 00:35:41,367
I firmly believe that an animator's job

797
00:35:41,367 --> 00:35:43,808
is only half done when you export an animation.

798
00:35:43,808 --> 00:35:45,769
Working gameplay is rarely about

799
00:35:45,769 --> 00:35:46,950
the animation you're working on.

800
00:35:46,950 --> 00:35:49,812
More often than not, it's about the animation

801
00:35:49,812 --> 00:35:52,833
before and after, and these are just as important,

802
00:35:52,833 --> 00:35:54,995
giving much more context to the current move.

803
00:35:56,137 --> 00:36:00,019
When, with each animation, ask yourself these questions.

804
00:36:00,019 --> 00:36:01,581
How will it be perceived by the player?

805
00:36:01,581 --> 00:36:03,022
Does it read well?

806
00:36:03,022 --> 00:36:06,664
Does it look and feel good when interacting with it?

807
00:36:06,664 --> 00:36:09,787
Does the look match the purpose?

808
00:36:09,787 --> 00:36:11,628
Should I take control away from the player?

809
00:36:11,628 --> 00:36:14,310
If so, when do I get it back?

810
00:36:14,310 --> 00:36:18,012
When can I interrupt the animation and does it feel right?

811
00:36:18,012 --> 00:36:19,333
And what is the most common animation

812
00:36:19,333 --> 00:36:21,035
before and after this one?

813
00:36:21,035 --> 00:36:22,596
Is it worth creating a custom transition?

814
00:36:24,072 --> 00:36:26,553
This will vastly improve how your animation feels.

815
00:36:26,553 --> 00:36:29,014
Block it out, export it, and get it how you think

816
00:36:29,014 --> 00:36:30,215
it will work in the game.

817
00:36:30,215 --> 00:36:31,736
Play it, play it again.

818
00:36:31,736 --> 00:36:34,057
Give the controller to someone else.

819
00:36:34,057 --> 00:36:34,777
Watch how they play it.

820
00:36:34,777 --> 00:36:38,779
Always ask, how does it feel?

821
00:36:38,779 --> 00:36:45,542
Make adjustments, re-export, test, adjust, and repeat.

822
00:36:45,542 --> 00:36:47,703
This applies to any animation or system

823
00:36:47,703 --> 00:36:49,163
you can expect a player to interact with.

824
00:36:50,566 --> 00:36:52,868
Understand what your game designers actually want.

825
00:36:52,868 --> 00:36:53,628
Talk to them.

826
00:36:53,628 --> 00:36:55,750
Gameplay animation is a collaborative process.

827
00:36:55,750 --> 00:36:57,931
Find your natural rhythm and flow

828
00:36:57,931 --> 00:37:00,373
and your game will feel much better for it.

829
00:37:00,373 --> 00:37:04,216
And as many of us said before, get it in the game.

